BUG 1 — CRITICAL: Navigation scroll sync broken

Problem:
When F7 is pressed, pane A scrolls to the target row
via rowRefsA[target].scrollIntoView().
Pane B is supposed to sync via the scroll listener.
But scrollIntoView() on a <tr> element does not
reliably trigger the scroll event on the parent
scroll container. Pane B gets wrong or no scroll.

Fix:
Do NOT use scrollIntoView() for navigation.
Instead, calculate the target scrollTop manually
and set it directly on BOTH scroll containers.

Replace the navigation scroll logic with:
```typescript
function scrollToRow(rowIndex: number) {
  const ROW_HEIGHT = 37 // px — must match actual tr height
  const containerHeight = scrollRefA.current?.clientHeight ?? 0
  
  // Calculate scrollTop that centres the target row
  const targetScrollTop = Math.max(
    0,
    (rowIndex * ROW_HEIGHT) - (containerHeight / 2) + (ROW_HEIGHT / 2)
  )
  
  // Set both containers directly — no listener needed
  isSyncingRef.current = true
  
  if (scrollRefA.current) {
    scrollRefA.current.scrollTop = targetScrollTop
  }
  if (scrollRefB.current) {
    scrollRefB.current.scrollTop = targetScrollTop
  }
  
  requestAnimationFrame(() => {
    isSyncingRef.current = false
  })
}
```

Call scrollToRow(changeIndex[pos]) from navigateTo()
instead of rowRef.scrollIntoView().

ROW_HEIGHT must match the actual rendered row height.
Measure it: open browser devtools, inspect a <tr>,
check its offsetHeight. Typical value is 36-40px.
Use the actual value, not an estimate.

After this fix, both panes scroll to identical
scrollTop on every navigation press.
They cannot go out of sync because both are set
to the same value in the same synchronous call.

Also remove rowRefsA and rowRefsB entirely —
they are no longer needed.

